# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agile-devops
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The practitioners cite inspiration from new practices at the time including extreme programming, scrum, dynamic systems development method, adaptive software development, and being sympathetic to the need for an alternative to documentation-driven, heavyweight software development processes.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Many software development practices emerged from the agile mindset.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] These agile-based practices, sometimes called *Agile* (with a capital A), include requirements, discovery, and solutions improvement through the collaborative effort of self-organizing and cross-functional teams with their customer(s)/end user(s).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] While there is much anecdotal evidence that the agile mindset and agile-based practices improve the software development process, the empirical evidence is limited and less than conclusive.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Iterative and incremental software development methods can be traced back as early as 1957, with evolutionary project management and adaptive software development emerging in the early 1970s.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] During the 1990s, a number of *lightweight* software development methods evolved in reaction to the prevailing *heavyweight* methods (often referred to collectively as *waterfall*) that critics described as overly regulated, planned, and micromanaged.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] These lightweight methods included rapid application development (RAD), from 1991; the unified process (UP) and dynamic systems development method (DSDM), both from 1994; Scrum, from 1995; Crystal Clear and extreme programming (XP), both from 1996; and feature-driven development (FDD), from 1997.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Although these all originated before the publication of the *Agile Manifesto*, they are now collectively referred to as agile software development methods.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Already since 1991 similar changes had been underway in manufacturing and management thinking derived from lean management.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In 2001, seventeen software developers met at a resort in Snowbird, Utah to discuss lightweight development methods.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] They were Kent Beck (Extreme Programming), Ward Cunningham (Extreme Programming), Dave Thomas (Pragmatic Programming, Ruby), Jeff Sutherland (Scrum), Ken Schwaber (Scrum), Jim Highsmith (Adaptive Software Development), Alistair Cockburn (Crystal), Robert C.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Martin (SOLID), Mike Beedle (Scrum), Arie van Bennekum, Martin Fowler (OOAD and UML), James Grenning, Andrew Hunt (Pragmatic Programming, Ruby), Ron Jeffries (Extreme Programming), Jon Kern, Brian Marick (Ruby, Test-driven development), and Steve Mellor (OOA).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The group, The Agile Alliance, published the *Manifesto for Agile Software Development*.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In 2005, a group headed by Cockburn and Highsmith wrote an addendum of project management principles, the PM Declaration of Interdependence, to guide software project management according to agile software development methods.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In 2009, a group working with Martin wrote an extension of software development principles, the Software Craftsmanship Manifesto, to guide agile software development according to professional conduct and mastery.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Welcome changing requirements, even in late development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Deliver working software frequently (weeks rather than months).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Close, daily cooperation between business people and developers.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Projects are built around motivated individuals, who should be trusted.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Face-to-face conversation is the best form of communication (co-location).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Working software is the primary measure of progress.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Sustainable development, able to maintain a constant pace.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Continuous attention to technical excellence and good design.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Simplicity—the art of maximizing the amount of work not done—is essential.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Best architectures, requirements, and designs emerge from self-organizing teams.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Regularly, the team reflects on how to become more effective, and adjusts accordingly.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Most agile development methods break product development work into small increments that minimize the amount of up-front planning and design.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Iterations, or sprints, are short time frames (timeboxes) that typically last from one to four weeks.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Each iteration involves a cross-functional team working in all functions: planning, analysis, design, coding, unit testing, and acceptance testing.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] At the end of the iteration a working product is demonstrated to stakeholders.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This minimizes overall risk and allows the product to adapt to changes quickly.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] An iteration might not add enough functionality to warrant a market release, but the goal is to have an available release (with minimal bugs) at the end of each iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Through incremental development, products have room to "fail often and early" throughout each iterative phase instead of drastically on a final release date.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Multiple iterations might be required to release a product or new features.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The 6th principle of the agile manifesto for software development states, "The most efficient and effective method of conveying information to and within a development team is face-to-face conversation".
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The manifesto, written in 2001 when video conferencing was not widely used, states this in relation to the communication of information, not necessarily that a team should be co-located.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The principle of co-location is that co-workers on the same team should be situated together to better establish the identity as a team and to improve communication.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This enables face-to-face interaction, ideally in front of a whiteboard, that reduces the cycle time typically taken when questions and answers are mediated through phone, persistent chat, wiki, or email.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] With the widespread adoption of remote working during the COVID-19 pandemic and changes to tooling, more studies have been conducted around co-location and distributed working which show that co-location is increasingly less relevant.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] No matter which development method is followed, every team should include a customer representative (known as *product owner* in Scrum).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This representative is agreed by stakeholders to act on their behalf and makes a personal commitment to being available for developers to answer questions throughout the iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] At the end of each iteration, the project stakeholders together with the customer representative review progress and re-evaluate priorities with a view to optimizing the return on investment (ROI) and ensuring alignment with customer needs and company goals.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The importance of stakeholder satisfaction, detailed by frequent interaction and review at the end of each phase, is why the approach is often denoted as a customer-centered methodology.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In agile software development, an **information radiator** is a (normally large) physical display, board with sticky notes or similar, located prominently near the development team, where passers-by can see it.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It presents an up-to-date summary of the product development status.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A build light indicator may also be used to inform a team about the current status of their product development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A common characteristic in agile software development is the daily stand-up (known as *daily scrum* in the Scrum framework).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In a brief session (e.g., 15 minutes), team members review collectively how they are progressing toward their goal and agree whether they need to adapt their approach.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] To keep to the agreed time limit, teams often use simple coded questions (such as what they completed the previous day, what they aim to complete that day, and whether there are any impediments or risks to progress), and delay detailed discussions and problem resolution until after the stand-up.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This is predicated on designing and building quality in from the beginning and being able to demonstrate software for customers at any point, or at least at the end of every iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Compared to traditional software engineering, agile software development mainly targets complex systems and product development with dynamic, indeterministic and non-linear properties.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Accurate estimates, stable plans, and predictions are often hard to get in early stages, and confidence in them is likely to be low.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile practitioners use their free will to reduce the "leap of faith" that is needed before any evidence of value can be obtained.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Requirements and design are held to be emergent.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Big up-front specifications would probably cause a lot of waste in such cases, i.e., are not economically sound.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] These basic arguments and previous industry experiences, learned from years of successes and failures, have helped shape agile development's favor of adaptive, iterative and evolutionary development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Development methods exist on a continuum from *adaptive* to *predictive*.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development methods lie on the *adaptive* side of this continuum.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] One key of adaptive development methods is a *rolling wave* approach to schedule planning, which identifies milestones but leaves flexibility in the path to reach them, and also allows for the milestones themselves to change.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Risk analysis can be used to choose between adaptive (*agile* or *value-driven*) and predictive (*plan-driven*) methods.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] One of the differences between agile software development methods and waterfall is the approach to quality and testing.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In the waterfall model, work moves through software development life cycle (SDLC) phases—with one phase being completed before another can start—hence the ***testing phase*** is separate and follows a ***build phase***.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In agile software development, however, testing is completed in the same iteration as programming.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Because testing is done in every iteration—which develops a small piece of the software—users can frequently use those new pieces of software and validate the value.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] After the users know the real value of the updated piece of software, they can make better decisions about the software's future.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Having a value retrospective and software re-planning session in each iteration—Scrum typically has iterations of just two weeks—helps the team continuously adapt its plans so as to maximize the value it delivers.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This follows a pattern similar to the plan-do-check-act (PDCA) cycle, as the work is *planned*, *done*, *checked* (in the review and retrospective), and any changes agreed are *acted* upon.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This iterative approach supports a *product* rather than a *project* mindset.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This provides greater flexibility throughout the development process; whereas on projects the requirements are defined and locked down from the very beginning, making it difficult to change them later.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Iterative product development allows the software to evolve in response to changes in business environment or market requirements.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In a letter to *IEEE Computer*, Steven Rakitin expressed cynicism about agile software development, calling it "yet another attempt to undermine the discipline of software engineering" and translating "working software over comprehensive documentation" as "we want to spend all our time coding.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This is disputed by proponents of agile software development, who state that developers should write documentation if that is the best way to achieve the relevant goals, but that there are often better ways to achieve those goals than writing static documentation.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development methods support a broad range of the software development life cycle.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Some methods focus on the practices (e.g., XP, pragmatic programming, agile modeling), while some focus on managing the flow of work (e.g., Scrum, Kanban).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Some support activities for requirements specification and development (e.g., FDD), while some seek to cover the full development life cycle (e.g., DSDM, RUP).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development is supported by a number of concrete practices, covering areas like requirements, design, modeling, coding, testing, planning, risk management, process, quality, etc.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Acceptance test–driven development (ATDD) is a development methodology based on communication between the business customers, the developers, and the testers.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] ATDD encompasses many of the same practices as specification by example (SBE), behavior-driven development (BDD), example-driven development (EDD), and support-driven development also called story test–driven development (SDD).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] All these processes aid developers and testers in understanding the customer's needs before implementation and allow customers to be able to converse in their own domain language.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile modeling (AM) is a methodology for modeling and documenting software systems based on best practices.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It is a collection of values and principles that can be applied on an (agile) software development project.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This methodology is more flexible than traditional modeling methods, making it a better fit in a fast-changing environment.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It is part of the agile software development tool kit.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile testing is a software testing practice that follows the principles of agile software development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile testing involves all members of a cross-functional agile team, with special expertise contributed by testers, to ensure delivering the business value desired by the customer at frequent intervals, working at a sustainable pace.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Specification by example is used to capture examples of desired and undesired behavior and guide coding.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Within agile project management, product backlog refers to a prioritized list of functionality which a product should contain.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It is sometimes referred to as a to-do list, and is considered an 'artifact' (a form of documentation) within the scrum software development framework.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The product backlog is referred to with different names in different project management frameworks, such as *product backlog* in scrum, work item list in disciplined agile, and option pool in lean.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In the scrum framework, creation and continuous maintenance of the product backlog is part of the responsibility of the product owner.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Behavior-driven development (BDD) is an agile software development method centered around collaboration between business and IT professionals that have a stake in finding a solution for a complex problem.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The core objective is to achieve a shared understanding of the problem.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Continuous integration (CI) is the practice of integrating source code changes frequently and ensuring that the integrated codebase is in a workable state.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Typically, developers merge changes to an integration branch, and an automated system builds and tests the software system.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Often, the automated process runs on each commit or runs on a schedule such as once a day.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Grady Booch first proposed the term CI in 1991, although he did not advocate integrating multiple times a day, but later, CI came to include that aspect.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A cross-functional team (XFN), also known as a multidisciplinary team or interdisciplinary team, is a group of people with different functional expertise working toward a common goal.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It may include people from finance, marketing, operations, and human resources departments.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Typically, it includes employees from all levels of an organization.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Members may also come from outside an organization (in particular, from suppliers, key customers, or consultants).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A stand-up meeting (stum) is a meeting in which attendees typically participate while standing, usually at around 10am.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The discomfort of standing for long periods is intended to keep the meetings short.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In the literature, different terms refer to the notion of method adaptation, including 'method tailoring', 'method fragment adaptation' and 'situational method engineering'.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Situation-appropriateness should be considered as a distinguishing characteristic between agile methods and more plan-driven software development methods, with agile methods allowing product development teams to adapt working practices according to the needs of individual products.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Potentially, most agile methods could be suitable for method tailoring, such as DSDM tailored in a CMM context. and XP tailored with the *Rule Description Practices* (RDP) technique.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Not all agile proponents agree, however, with Schwaber noting "that is how we got into trouble in the first place, thinking that the problem was not having a perfect methodology.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Efforts [should] center on the changes [needed] in the enterprise".
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Bas Vodde reinforced this viewpoint, suggesting that unlike traditional, large methodologies that require you to pick and choose elements, Scrum provides the basics on top of which you add additional elements to localize and contextualize its use.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Practitioners seldom use system development methods, or agile methods specifically, by the book, often choosing to omit or tailor some of the practices of a method in order to create an in-house method.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In practice, methods can be tailored using various tools.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Generic process modeling languages such as Unified Modeling Language can be used to tailor software development methods.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, dedicated tools for method engineering such as the Essence Theory of Software Engineering of SEMAT also exist.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] There are many conflicting viewpoints on whether all of these are effective or indeed fit the definition of agile development, and this remains an active and ongoing area of research.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] When agile software development is applied in a distributed setting (with teams dispersed across multiple business locations), it is commonly referred to as distributed agile software development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The goal is to leverage the unique benefits offered by each approach.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Distributed development allows organizations to build software by strategically setting up teams in different parts of the globe, virtually building software round-the-clock (more commonly referred to as follow-the-sun model).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] On the other hand, agile development provides increased transparency, continuous feedback, and more flexibility when responding to changes.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development methods were initially seen as best suitable for non-critical product developments, thereby excluded from use in regulated domains such as medical devices, pharmaceutical, financial, nuclear systems, automotive, and avionics sectors, etc.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, in the last several years, there have been several initiatives for the adaptation of agile methods for these domains.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] There are numerous standards that may apply in regulated domains, including ISO 26262, ISO 9000, ISO 9001, and ISO/IEC 15504.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Although agile software development methods can be used with any programming paradigm or language in practice, they were originally closely associated with object-oriented environments such as Smalltalk, Lisp and later Java, C#.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The initial adopters of agile methods were usually small to medium-sized teams working on unprecedented systems with requirements that were difficult to finalize and likely to change as the system was being developed.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This section describes common problems that organizations encounter when they try to adopt agile software development methods as well as various techniques to measure the quality and performance of agile teams.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The *Agility measurement index*, amongst others, rates developments against five dimensions of product development (duration, risk, novelty, effort, and interaction).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Other techniques are based on measurable goals and one study suggests that velocity can be used as a metric of agility.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] There are also agile self-assessments to determine whether a team is using agile software development practices (Nokia test, Karlskrona test, 42 points test).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] One of the early studies reporting gains in quality, productivity, and business satisfaction by using agile software developments methods was a survey conducted by Shine Technologies from November 2002 to January 2003.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A similar survey, the *State of Agile*, is conducted every year starting in 2006 with thousands of participants from around the software development community.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This tracks trends on the perceived benefits of agility, lessons learned, and good practices.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Each survey has reported increasing numbers saying that agile software development helps them deliver software faster, improves their ability to manage changing customer priorities, and increases their productivity.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Surveys have also consistently shown better results with agile product development methods compared to classical project management.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In balance, there are reports that some feel that agile development methods are still too young to enable extensive academic research of their success.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Organizations and teams implementing agile software development often face difficulties transitioning from more traditional methods such as waterfall development, such as teams having an agile process forced on them.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] These are often termed *agile anti-patterns* or more commonly *agile smells*.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A goal of agile software development is to focus more on producing working software and less on documentation.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This is in contrast to waterfall models where the process is often highly controlled and minor changes to the system require significant revision of supporting documentation.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, this does not justify completely doing without any analysis or design at all.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Failure to pay attention to design can cause a team to proceed rapidly at first, but then to require significant rework as they attempt to scale up the system.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] One of the key features of agile software development is that it is iterative.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] When done correctly, agile software development allows the design to emerge as the system is developed and helps the team discover commonalities and opportunities for re-use.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In agile software development, *stories* (similar to use case descriptions) are typically used to define requirements and an *iteration* is a short period of time during which the team commits to specific goals.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Adding stories to an iteration in progress is detrimental to a good flow of work.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] These should be added to the product backlog and prioritized for a subsequent iteration or in rare cases the iteration could be cancelled.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This does not mean that a story cannot expand.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Teams must deal with new information, which may produce additional tasks for a story.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] If the new information prevents the story from being completed during the iteration, then it should be carried over to a subsequent iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, it should be prioritized against all remaining stories, as the new information may have changed the story's original priority.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development is often implemented as a grassroots effort in organizations by software development teams trying to optimize their development processes and ensure consistency in the software development life cycle.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] By not having sponsor support, teams may face difficulties and resistance from business partners, other development teams and management.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Additionally, they may suffer without appropriate funding and resources.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This increases the likelihood of failure.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The product owner is responsible for representing the business in the development activity and is often the most demanding role.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A common mistake is to fill the product owner role with someone from the development team.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This requires the team to make its own decisions on prioritization without real feedback from the business.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] They try to solve business issues internally or delay work as they reach outside the team for direction.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This often leads to distraction and a breakdown in collaboration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development requires teams to meet product commitments, which means they should focus on work for only that product.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, team members who appear to have spare capacity are often expected to take on other work, which makes it difficult for them to help complete the work to which their team had committed.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Teams may fall into the trap of spending too much time preparing or planning.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] This is a common trap for teams less familiar with agile software development where the teams feel obliged to have a complete understanding and specification of all stories.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Teams should be prepared to move forward with only those stories in which they have confidence, then during the iteration continue to discover and prepare work for subsequent iterations (often referred to as backlog refinement or grooming).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A daily standup should be a focused, timely meeting where all team members disseminate information.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] If problem-solving occurs, it often can involve only certain team members and potentially is not the best use of the entire team's time.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] If during the daily standup the team starts diving into problem-solving, it should be set aside until a sub-team can discuss, usually immediately after the standup completes.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] One of the intended benefits of agile software development is to empower the team to make choices, as they are closest to the problem.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Additionally, they should make choices as close to implementation as possible, to use more timely information in the decision.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] If team members are assigned tasks by others or too early in the process, the benefits of localized and timely decision making can be lost.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Being assigned work also constrains team members into certain roles (for example, team member A must always do the database work), which limits opportunities for cross-training.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Team members themselves can choose to take on tasks that stretch their abilities and provide cross-training opportunities.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In the Scrum framework, which claims to be consistent with agile values and principles, the *scrum master* role is accountable for ensuring the scrum process is followed and for coaching the scrum team through that process.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A common pitfall is for a scrum master to act as a contributor.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] While not prohibited by the Scrum framework, the scrum master needs to ensure they have the capacity to act in the role of scrum master first and not work on development tasks.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A scrum master's role is to facilitate the process rather than create the product.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Having the scrum master also multitasking may result in too many context switches to be productive.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Additionally, as a scrum master is responsible for ensuring roadblocks are removed so that the team can make forward progress, the benefit gained by individual tasks moving forward may not outweigh roadblocks that are deferred due to lack of capacity.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Due to the iterative nature of agile development, multiple rounds of testing are often needed.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Automated testing helps reduce the impact of repeated unit, integration, and regression tests and frees developers and testers to focus on higher value work.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Test automation also supports continued refactoring required by iterative software development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Allowing a developer to quickly run tests to confirm refactoring has not modified the functionality of the application may reduce the workload and increase confidence that cleanup efforts have not introduced new defects.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Focusing on delivering new functionality may result in increased technical debt.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The team must allow themselves time for defect remediation and refactoring.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Technical debt hinders planning abilities by increasing the amount of unscheduled work as production defects distract the team from further progress.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] As the system evolves it is important to refactor.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Over time the lack of constant maintenance causes increasing defects and development costs.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A common misconception is that agile software development allows continuous change, however an iteration backlog is an agreement of what work can be completed during an iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Having too much work-in-progress (WIP) results in inefficiencies such as context-switching and queueing.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The team must avoid feeling pressured into taking on additional work.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development fixes time (iteration duration), quality, and ideally resources in advance (though maintaining fixed resources may be difficult if developers are often pulled away from tasks to handle production incidents), while the scope remains variable.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The customer or product owner often pushes for a fixed scope for an iteration.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, teams should be reluctant to commit to the locked time, resources and scope (commonly known as the project management triangle).
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Efforts to add scope to the fixed time and resources of agile software development may result in decreased quality.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Due to the focused pace and continuous nature of agile practices, there is a heightened risk of burnout among members of the delivery team.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile project management is an iterative development process, where feedback is continuously gathered from users and stakeholders to create the right user experience.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Different methods can be used to perform an agile process, these include scrum, extreme programming, lean and kanban.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile project management metrics help reduce confusion, identify weak points, and measure team's performance throughout the development cycle.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Supply chain agility is the ability of a supply chain to cope with uncertainty and variability on offer and demand.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] An agile supply chain can increase and reduce its capacity rapidly, so it can adapt to a fast-changing customer demand.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Finally, strategic agility is the ability of an organisation to change its course of action as its environment is evolving.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The key for strategic agility is to recognize external changes early enough and to allocate resources to adapt to these changing environments.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile X techniques may also be called extreme project management.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] It is a variant of iterative life cycle where deliverables are submitted in stages.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The main difference between agile and iterative development is that agile methods complete small portions of the deliverables in each delivery cycle (iteration), while iterative methods evolve the entire set of deliverables over time, completing them near the end of the project.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Both iterative and agile methods were developed as a reaction to various obstacles that developed in more sequential forms of project organization.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] For example, as technology projects grow in complexity, end users tend to have difficulty defining the long-term requirements without being able to view progressive prototypes.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Projects that develop in iterations can constantly gather feedback to help refine those requirements.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile management also offers a simple framework promoting communication and reflection on past work amongst team members.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Teams who were using traditional waterfall planning and adopted the agile way of development typically go through a transformation phase and often take help from agile coaches who help guide the teams through a smoother transformation.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] There are typically two styles of agile coaching: push-based and pull-based agile coaching.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Here a "push-system" can refer to an upfront estimation of what tasks can be fitted into a sprint (pushing work) e.g. typical with scrum; whereas a "pull system" can refer to an environment where tasks are only performed when capacity is available.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile management approaches have also been employed and adapted to the business and government sectors.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development methods have been extensively used for development of software products and some of them use certain characteristics of software, such as object technologies.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] However, these techniques can be applied to the development of non-software products, such as computers, medical devices, food, clothing, and music.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development methods have been used in non-development IT infrastructure deployments and migrations.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Some of the wider principles of agile software development have also found application in general management (e.g., strategy, governance, risk, finance) under the terms business agility or agile business management.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software methodologies have also been adopted for use with the learning engineering process, an iterative data-informed process that applies human-centered design, and data informed decision-making to support learners and their development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile software development paradigms can be used in other areas of life such as raising children.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Its success in child development might be founded on some basic management principles: communication, adaptation, and awareness.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] In a TED Talk, Bruce Feiler shared how he applied basic agile paradigms to household management and raising children.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Agile practices have been cited as potentially inefficient in large organizations and certain types of development.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Many organizations believe that agile software development methodologies are too extreme and adopt a hybrid approach that mixes elements of agile software development and plan-driven approaches.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Some methods, such as dynamic systems development method (DSDM), attempt this in a disciplined way, without sacrificing fundamental principles.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The increasing adoption of agile practices has also been criticized as being a management fad that simply describes existing good practices under new jargon, promotes a one-size-fits-all mindset towards development strategies, and wrongly emphasizes method over results.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Alistair Cockburn organized a celebration of the 10th anniversary of the *Manifesto for Agile Software Development* in Snowbird, Utah on 12 February 2011, gathering some 30+ people who had been involved at the original meeting and since.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The "Manifesto" may have had a negative impact on higher education management and leadership, where it suggested to administrators that slower traditional and deliberative processes should be replaced with more "nimble" ones.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] The concept rarely found acceptance among university faculty.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Another criticism is that in many ways, agile management and traditional management practices end up being in opposition to one another.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A common criticism of this practice is that the time spent attempting to learn and implement the practice is too costly, despite potential benefits.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] A transition from traditional management to agile management requires total submission to agile and a firm commitment from all members of the organization to seeing the process through.
[src:agile-devops/agile-software-development] Issues like unequal results across the organization, too much change for employees to handle, or a lack of guarantees at the end of the transformation are just a few examples.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:agile-devops/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:agile-devops/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:agile-devops/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:agile-devops/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:agile-devops/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:agile-devops/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:agile-devops/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:agile-devops/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:agile-devops/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:agile-devops/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:agile-devops/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:agile-devops/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:agile-devops/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:agile-devops/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:agile-devops/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:agile-devops/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:agile-devops/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:agile-devops/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:agile-devops/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:agile-devops/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:agile-devops/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:agile-devops/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:agile-devops/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:agile-devops/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:agile-devops/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The methodology takes its name from the idea that the beneficial elements of traditional software engineering practices are taken to "extreme" levels.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] As an example, code reviews are considered a beneficial practice; taken to the extreme, code can be reviewed *continuously* (i.e. the practice of pair programming).
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Kent Beck developed extreme programming during his work on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System (C3) payroll project.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Beck became the C3 project leader in March 1996.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] He began to refine the development methodology used in the project and wrote a book on the methodology (*Extreme Programming Explained*, published in October 1999).
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Chrysler cancelled the C3 project in February 2000, after seven years, when Daimler-Benz acquired the company.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Ward Cunningham was another major influence on XP.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Many extreme-programming practices have been around for some time; the methodology takes "best practices" to extreme levels.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] For example, the "practice of test-first development, planning and writing tests before each micro-increment" was used as early as NASA's Project Mercury, in the early 1960s.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] To shorten the total development time, some formal test documents (such as for acceptance testing) have been developed in parallel with (or shortly before) the software being ready for testing.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] A NASA independent test group can write the test procedures, based on formal requirements and logical limits, before programmers write the software and integrate it with the hardware.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] XP takes this concept to the extreme level, writing automated tests (sometimes inside software modules) which validate the operation of even small sections of software coding, rather than only testing the larger features.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Rapidly changing requirements demanded shorter product life-cycles, and often clashed with traditional methods of software development.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System (C3) started in order to determine the best way to use object technologies, using the payroll systems at Chrysler as the object of research, with Smalltalk as the language and GemStone as the data access layer.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Chrysler brought in Kent Beck, a prominent Smalltalk practitioner, to do performance tuning on the system, but his role expanded as he noted several problems with the development process.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] He took this opportunity to propose and implement some changes in development practices - based on his work with his frequent collaborator, Ward Cunningham.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Beck invited Ron Jeffries to the project to help develop and refine these methods.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Jeffries thereafter acted as a coach to instill the practices as habits in the C3 team.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Information about the principles and practices behind XP disseminated to the wider world through discussions on the original wiki, Cunningham's WikiWikiWeb.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Various contributors discussed and expanded upon the ideas, and some spin-off methodologies resulted (see agile software development).
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Also, XP concepts have been explained, for several years, using a hypertext system map on the XP website at http://www.extremeprogramming.org c.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Beck edited a series of books on XP, beginning with his own *Extreme Programming Explained* (1999, ISBN 0-201-61641-6), spreading his ideas to a much larger audience.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Authors in the series went through various aspects attending XP and its practices.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The series included a book critical of the practices.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] XP attempts to reduce the cost of changes in requirements by having multiple short development cycles, rather than a long one.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] In this doctrine, changes are a natural, inescapable and desirable aspect of software-development projects, and should be planned for, instead of attempting to define a stable set of requirements.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming also introduces a number of basic values, principles and practices on top of the agile methodology.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] XP describes four basic activities that are performed within the software development process: coding, testing, listening, and designing.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Each of those activities is described below.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The advocates of XP argue that the only truly important product of the system development process is code – software instructions that a computer can interpret.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Without code, there is no working product.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Coding can be used to figure out the most suitable solution.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Coding can also help to communicate thoughts about programming problems.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] A programmer dealing with a complex programming problem, or finding it hard to explain the solution to fellow programmers, might code it in a simplified manner and use the code to demonstrate what they mean.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Code, say the proponents of this position, is always clear and concise and cannot be interpreted in more than one way.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Other programmers can give feedback on this code by also coding their thoughts.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Testing is central to extreme programming.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming's approach is that if a little testing can eliminate a few flaws, a lot of testing can eliminate many more flaws.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] System-wide integration testing was encouraged initially as a daily end-of-day activity for early detection of incompatible interfaces.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] However, system-wide integration testing has been reduced to weekly or less often depending on the stability of the overall interfaces in the system.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Programmers must listen to what the customers need the system to do, and what "business logic" is needed.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] They must understand these needs well enough to give the customer feedback about the technical aspects of how the problem might be solved, as well as if the problem can be solved within the given constraints.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Communication between the customer and programmer is further addressed in the *planning game*.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] From the point of view of simplicity, one could say that system development doesn't need more than coding, testing and listening.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] If those activities are performed well, the result should always be a system that works.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] One can come a long way without designing but at a given time one will get stuck.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The system becomes too complex and the dependencies within the system cease to be clear.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This can be avoided by creating a design structure that organizes the logic in the system.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Good design will avoid many dependencies within a system; this means that changing one part of the system will not affect other parts of the system.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming initially recognized four values in 1999: communication, simplicity, feedback, and courage.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] A new value, respect, was added in the second edition of *Extreme Programming Explained*.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Building software systems requires communicating system requirements to the developers of the system.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] In formal software development methodologies, this task is accomplished through documentation.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming techniques can be viewed as methods for rapidly building and disseminating institutional knowledge among members of a development team.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The goal is to give all developers a shared view of the system which matches the view held by the users of the system.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] To this end, extreme programming favors simple designs, common metaphors, collaboration of users and programmers, frequent verbal communication, and feedback.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming encourages starting with the simplest solution.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extra functionality can then be added later.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The difference between this approach and more conventional system development methods is the focus on designing and coding for the needs of today instead of those of tomorrow, next week, or next month.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This is sometimes summed up as the "You aren't gonna need it" (YAGNI) approach.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Proponents of XP acknowledge the disadvantage that this can sometimes entail more effort tomorrow to change the system; their claim is that this is more than compensated for by the advantage of not investing in possible future requirements that might change before they become relevant.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Coding and designing for uncertain future requirements implies the risk of spending resources on something that might not be needed, while perhaps delaying crucial features.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Related to the "communication" value, simplicity in design and coding should improve the quality of communication.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] A simple design with very simple code could be easily understood by most programmers in the team.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Feedback is closely related to communication and simplicity.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Flaws in the system are easily communicated by writing a unit test that proves a certain piece of code will break.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The direct feedback from the system tells programmers to recode this part.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] A customer is able to test the system periodically according to the functional requirements, known as *user stories*.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] To quote Kent Beck, "Optimism is an occupational hazard of programming.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] One is the commandment to always design and code for today and not for tomorrow.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This is an effort to avoid getting bogged down in design and requiring a lot of effort to implement anything else.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Courage enables developers to feel comfortable with refactoring their code when necessary.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This means reviewing the existing system and modifying it so that future changes can be implemented more easily.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Another example of courage is knowing when to throw code away: courage to remove source code that is obsolete, no matter how much effort was used to create that source code.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Also, courage means persistence: a programmer might be stuck on a complex problem for an entire day, then solve the problem quickly the next day, but only if they are persistent.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The respect value includes respect for others as well as self-respect.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Programmers should never commit changes that break compilation, that make existing unit-tests fail, or that otherwise delay the work of their peers.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Members respect their own work by writing high quality code and seeking for the best design for the solution at hand through refactoring.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Adopting the four earlier values leads to respect gained from others in the team.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Nobody on the team should feel unappreciated or ignored.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This ensures a high level of motivation and encourages loyalty toward the team and toward the goal of the project.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This value is dependent upon the other values, and is oriented toward teamwork.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The first version of rules for XP was published in 1999 by Don Wells at the XP website.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] 29 rules are given in the categories of planning, managing, designing, coding, and testing.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Planning, managing and designing are called out explicitly to counter claims that XP doesn't support those activities.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Another version of XP rules was proposed by Ken Auer in XP/Agile Universe 2003.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] He felt XP was defined by its rules, not its practices (which are subject to more variation and ambiguity).
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] He defined two categories: "Rules of Engagement" which dictate the environment in which software development can take place effectively, and "Rules of Play" which define the minute-by-minute activities and rules within the framework of the Rules of Engagement.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The principles that form the basis of XP are based on the values just described and are intended to foster decisions in a system development project.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The principles are intended to be more concrete than the values and more easily translated to guidance in a practical situation.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming sees feedback as most useful if it is done frequently and promptly.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] It stresses that minimal delay between an action and its feedback is critical to learning and making changes.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Unlike traditional system development methods, contact with the customer occurs in more frequent iterations.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The customer has clear insight into the system that is being developed, and can give feedback and steer the development as needed.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] With frequent feedback from the customer, a mistaken design decision made by the developer will be noticed and corrected quickly, before the developer spends much time implementing it.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Unit tests contribute to the rapid feedback principle.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] When writing code, running the unit test provides direct feedback as to how the system reacts to the changes made.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This includes running not only the unit tests that test the developer's code, but running in addition all unit tests against all the software, using an automated process that can be initiated by a single command.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This is about treating every problem as if its solution were "extremely simple".
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Traditional system development methods say to plan for the future and to code for reusability.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming rejects these ideas.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The advocates of extreme programming say that making big changes all at once does not work.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming applies incremental changes: for example, a system might have small releases every three weeks.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] When many little steps are made, the customer has more control over the development process and the system that is being developed.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The principle of embracing change is about not working against changes but embracing them.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] For instance, if at one of the iterative meetings it appears that the customer's requirements have changed dramatically, programmers are to embrace this and plan the new requirements for the next iteration.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The practices in XP have been heavily debated.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Proponents of extreme programming claim that by having the on-site customer request changes informally, the process becomes flexible, and saves the cost of formal overhead.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Critics of XP claim this can lead to costly rework and project scope creep beyond what was previously agreed or funded.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Change-control boards are a sign that there are potential conflicts in project objectives and constraints between multiple users.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] XP's expedited methods are somewhat dependent on programmers being able to assume a unified client viewpoint so the programmer can concentrate on coding, rather than documentation of compromise objectives and constraints.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This also applies when multiple programming organizations are involved, particularly organizations which compete for shares of projects.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Critics have noted several potential drawbacks, including problems with unstable requirements, no documented compromises of user conflicts, and a lack of an overall design specification or document.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Thoughtworks has claimed reasonable success on distributed XP projects with up to sixty people.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] In 2004, industrial extreme programming (IXP) was introduced as an evolution of XP.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] It is intended to bring the ability to work in large and distributed teams.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] It now has 23 practices and flexible values.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] In 2003, Matt Stephens and Doug Rosenberg published *Extreme Programming Refactored: The Case Against XP*, which questioned the value of the XP process and suggested ways in which it could be improved.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] This triggered a lengthy debate in articles, Internet newsgroups, and web-site chat areas.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The core argument of the book is that XP's practices are interdependent but that few practical organizations are willing/able to adopt all the practices; therefore the entire process fails.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] The book also makes other criticisms, and it draws a likeness of XP's "collective ownership" model to socialism in a negative manner.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Certain aspects of XP have changed since the publication of *Extreme Programming Refactored*; in particular, XP now accommodates modifications to the practices as long as the required objectives are still met.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] XP also uses increasingly generic terms for processes.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Some argue that these changes invalidate previous criticisms; others claim that this is simply watering the process down.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Other authors have tried to reconcile XP with the older methodologies in order to form a unified methodology.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Some of these XP sought to replace, such as the waterfall methodology; example *Project Lifecycles: Waterfall*, Rapid Application Development (RAD), etc.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] JPMorgan Chase & Co. tried combining XP with the computer programming methods of capability maturity model integration (CMMI), and Six Sigma.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] They found that the three systems reinforced each other well, leading to better development, and did not mutually contradict.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Extreme programming's initial buzz and controversial tenets, such as pair programming and continuous design, have attracted particular criticisms, such as the ones coming from McBreen, Boehm and Turner, Matt Stephens and Doug Rosenberg.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] Many of the criticisms, however, are believed by Agile practitioners to be misunderstandings of agile development.
[src:agile-devops/extreme-programming] In particular, extreme programming has been reviewed and critiqued by Matt Stephens's and Doug Rosenberg's *Extreme Programming Refactored*.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:agile-devops/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Work items are visualized to give participants a view of progress and process, from start to finish—usually via a kanban board.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Work is pulled as capacity permits, rather than work being pushed into the process when requested.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In knowledge work and in software development, the aim is to provide a visual process management system which aids decision-making about what, when, and how much to produce.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The underlying kanban method originated in lean manufacturing, which was inspired by the Toyota Production System.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] It has its origin in the late 1940s when the Toyota automotive company implemented a production system called just-in-time, which had the objective of producing according to customer demand and identifying possible material shortages within the production line.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] But it was a team at Corbis that realized how this method devised by Toyota could become a process applicable to any type of organizational process.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Kanban is commonly used in software development in combination with methods and frameworks such as Scrum.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The diagram here shows a software development workflow on a kanban board.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The aim is to make the general workflow and the progress of individual items clear to participants and stakeholders.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Kanban is a strategy that aims to follow these in order to create systems that are efficient, effective, and predictable.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The Kanban Method is a specialized and detailed extrapolation of Kanban.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] As described in books on The Kanban Method for software development, the two primary practices of The Kanban Method are to visualize work and to limit work in progress (WIP).
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Four additional general practices of The Kanban Method listed in *Essential Kanban Condensed* are to make policies explicit, manage flow, implement feedback loops, and improve collaboratively.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The kanban board in the diagram above highlights the first three general practices of The Kanban Method.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Kanban manages workflow directly on the kanban board.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The WIP limits for development steps provide development teams immediate feedback on common workflow issues.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] For example, on the kanban board shown above, the "deployment" step has a WIP limit of five and there are currently five epics shown in that step.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] No more work items can move into deployment until one or more epics complete that step (moving to "delivered").
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] This prevents the "deployment" step from being overwhelmed.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Team members working on "feature acceptance" (the previous step) might get stuck because they can't deploy new epics.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] They can see why immediately on the board and help with the current epic deployments.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Once the five epics in the "deployment" step are delivered, the two epics from the "ready" sub-column of "feature acceptance" (the previous step) can be moved to the "deployment" column.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] When those two epics are delivered, no other epics can be deployed (assuming no new epics are ready).
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Now, team members working on deployment are stuck.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] They can see why immediately and help with feature acceptance.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In a Kanban board setup, swimlanes are used to visually organize work into different stages of a process, ensuring clarity and focus.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] For efficient workflow management, it is crucial to maintain distinct swimlanes for key phases such as requirements, development, testing, and closed/completed tasks.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Specifically, testing stories should always be placed within the designated "Testing" swimlane.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] This separation ensures that testing activities are easily trackable and not intermingled with other stories in development or other stages.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] By keeping testing tasks within their own swimlane, teams can quickly identify bottlenecks, prioritize issues, and maintain the integrity of the testing process without cross-contamination from development or requirement phases.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] This structure leads to clearer workflows and enhances team collaboration.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] This workflow control works similarly for every step.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Problems are visual and evident immediately, and re-planning can be done continuously.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] The work management is made possible by limiting work in progress in a way team members can see and track at all times.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In 2009, Don Reinertsen published a book on second-generation lean product-development which describes the adoption of the kanban system and the use of data collection and an economic model for management decision-making.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Another early contribution came from Corey Ladas, whose 2008 book *Scrumban* suggested that kanban could improve scrum for software development.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Ladas saw scrumban as the transition from scrum to kanban.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Jim Benson and Tonianne DeMaria Barry published *Personal Kanban*, applying kanban to individuals and small teams, in 2011.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In *Kanban from the Inside* (2014), Mike Burrows explained kanban's principles, practices and underlying values and related them to earlier theories and models.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In *Agile Project Management with Kanban* (2015), Eric Brechner provides an overview of kanban in practice at Microsoft and Xbox.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] *Kanban Change Leadership* (2015), by Klaus Leopold and Siegfried Kaltenecker, explained the method from the perspective of change management and provided guidance to change-initiatives.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In 2016 Lean Kanban University Press published a condensed guide to the method, incorporating improvements and extensions from the early kanban projects.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] In 2020 John Coleman and Daniel Vacanti published *The Kanban Guide* to describe the minimal conditions needed to operate a Kanban system.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Colleen Johnson, Daniel Vacanti, and Prateek Singh published The Kanban Pocket Guide in 2022, which helps practitioners navigate the Kanban practices.
[src:agile-devops/kanban-development] Will Seele and Daniel Vacanti also published the Flow Metrics for Scrum Teams book in 2022 to bring the benefits of metrics commonly used in Kanban to Scrum teams.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] While reviewing, the observer also considers the "strategic" direction of the work, coming up with ideas for improvements and likely future problems to address.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] This is intended to free the driver to focus all of their attention on the "tactical" aspects of completing the current task, using the observer as a safety net and guide.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Pair programming increases the human-hours required to deliver code compared to programmers working individually.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] However, the resulting code has fewer defects.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Along with code development time, other factors like field support costs and quality assurance also figure into the return on investment.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Pair programming might theoretically offset these expenses by reducing defects in the programs.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] In addition to preventing mistakes as they are made, other intangible benefits may exist.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] For example, the courtesy of rejecting phone calls or other distractions while working together, taking fewer breaks at agreed-upon intervals or sharing breaks to return phone calls (but returning to work quickly since someone is waiting).
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] One member of the team might have more focus and help drive or awaken the other if they lose focus, and that role might periodically change.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] One member might know about a topic or technique that the other does not, which might eliminate delays to finding or testing a solution, or allow for a better solution, thus effectively expanding the skill set, knowledge, and experience of a programmer as compared to working alone.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Each of these intangible benefits, and many more, may be challenging to accurately measure but can contribute to more efficient working hours.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] 3. they stand in different relationships to the problem by their functional roles.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] In an attempt to share goals and plans, the programmers must overtly negotiate a shared course of action when a conflict arises between them.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] In doing so, they consider a larger number of ways of solving the problem than a single programmer alone might do.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] This significantly improves the design quality of the program as it reduces the chances of selecting a poor method.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] In an online survey of pair programmers from 2000, 96% of programmers stated that they enjoyed working more while pair programming than programming alone.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Furthermore, 95% said that they were more confident in their work when they pair programmed.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] However, as the survey was among self-selected pair programmers, it did not account for programmers who were forced to pair program.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Knowledge is constantly shared between pair programmers, whether in the industry or in a classroom.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Many sources suggest that students show higher confidence when programming in pairs, and many learn whether it be from tips on programming language rules to overall design skills.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] In "promiscuous pairing", each programmer communicates and works with all the other programmers on the team rather than pairing only with one partner, which causes knowledge of the system to spread throughout the whole team.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Pair programming allows programmers to examine their partner's code and provide feedback, which is necessary to increase their own ability to develop monitoring mechanisms for their own learning activities.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Pair programming allows team members to share quickly, making them less likely to have agendas hidden from each other.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] This helps pair programmers learn to communicate more easily.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] There are both empirical studies and meta-analyses of pair programming.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] The empirical studies tend to examine the level of productivity and the quality of the code, while meta-analyses may focus on biases introduced by the process of testing and publishing.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] A meta-analysis found pairs typically consider more design alternatives than programmers working alone, arrive at simpler, more maintainable designs, and catch design defects earlier.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Although pair programmers may complete a task faster than a solo programmer, the total number of human-hours increases.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] A manager would have to balance faster completion of the work and reduced testing and debugging time against the higher cost of coding.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] The relative weight of these factors can vary by project and task.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] The benefit of pairing is greatest on tasks that the programmers do not fully understand before they begin: that is, challenging tasks that call for creativity and sophistication, and for novices as compared to experts.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Pair programming could be helpful for attaining high quality and correctness on complex programming tasks, but it would also increase the development effort (cost) significantly.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] On simple tasks, which the pair already fully understands, pairing results in a net drop in productivity.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] It may reduce the code development time but also risks reducing the quality of the program.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Productivity can also drop when novice–novice pairing is used without sufficient availability of a mentor to coach them.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Expert–expert pairing may seem to be the obvious choice for the highest productivity and can produce great results, but it often yields little insight into new ways to solve problems, as both parties are unlikely to question established practices.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Expert–novice pairing creates many opportunities for the expert to mentor the novice.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] This pairing can also introduce new ideas, as the novice is more likely to question established practices.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] The expert, now required to explain established practices, is also more likely to question them.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] However, in this pairing, an intimidated novice may passively "watch the master" and hesitate to participate meaningfully.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Also, some experts may not have the patience needed to allow constructive novice participation.
[src:agile-devops/pair-programming] Novice–novice pairing can produce results significantly better than two novices working independently, although this practice is generally discouraged because it is harder for novices to develop good habits without a proper role model.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum prescribes for teams to break work into goals to be completed within time-boxed iterations, called *sprints*.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Each sprint is no longer than one month and commonly lasts two weeks.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The scrum team assesses progress in time-boxed, stand-up meetings of up to 15 minutes, called *daily scrums*.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] At the end of the sprint, the team holds two further meetings: one sprint review to demonstrate the work for stakeholders and solicit feedback, and one internal sprint retrospective.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A person in charge of a scrum team is typically called a *scrum master*.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum teams should be cross-functional and self-managing.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Unlike sequential approaches, scrum is an iterative and incremental framework for product development.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum allows for continuous feedback and flexibility, requiring teams to self-organize by encouraging physical co-location or close online collaboration, and mandating frequent communication among all team members.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The flexible approach of scrum is based in part on the notion of requirement volatility, that stakeholders will change their requirements as the project evolves.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The use of the term *scrum* in software development came from a 1986 *Harvard Business Review* paper titled "The New New Product Development Game" by Hirotaka Takeuchi and Ikujiro Nonaka.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Based on case studies from manufacturing firms in the automotive, photocopier, and printer industries, the authors outlined a new approach to product development for increased speed and flexibility.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] They called this the rugby approach, as the process involves a single cross-functional team operating across multiple overlapping phases in which the team "tries to go the distance as a unit, passing the ball back and forth".
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The authors later developed scrum in their book, *The Knowledge Creating Company*.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] In the early 1990s, Ken Schwaber used what would become scrum at his company, Advanced Development Methods.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Jeff Sutherland, John Scumniotales, and Jeff McKenna developed a similar approach at Easel Corporation, referring to the approach with the term *scrum*.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Sutherland and Schwaber later worked together to integrate their ideas into a single framework, formally known as scrum.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Schwaber and Sutherland tested scrum and continually improved it, leading to the publication of a research paper in 1995, and the Manifesto for Agile Software Development in 2001.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Schwaber also collaborated with Babatunde Ogunnaike at DuPont Research Station and the University of Delaware to develop Scrum.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Ogunnaike believed that software development projects could often fail when initial conditions change if product management was not rooted in empirical practice.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] In 2002, Schwaber with others founded the Scrum Alliance and set up the *Certified Scrum* accreditation series.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Schwaber left the Scrum Alliance in late 2009 and subsequently founded Scrum.org, which oversees the parallel *Professional Scrum* accreditation series.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Since 2009, a public document called *The Scrum Guide* has been published and updated by Schwaber and Sutherland.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] It has been revised six times, with the most recent version having been published in November 2020.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A scrum team is organized into at least three categories of individuals: the product owner, developers, and the scrum master.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The product owner liaises with stakeholders, those who have an interest in the project's outcome, to communicate tasks and expectations with developers.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Developers in a scrum team organize work by themselves, with the facilitation of a scrum master.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The product owner focuses on the business side of product development and spends the majority of time liaising with stakeholders and the team.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The role is intended to primarily represent the product's stakeholders, the voice of the customer, or the desires of a committee, and bears responsibility for the delivery of business results.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Product owners manage the product backlog and are responsible for maximizing the value that a team delivers.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] However, it is the developers, not the product owner, who decide how much to do in each sprint and how to accomplish it.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] In scrum, the term *developer* or *team member* refers to anyone who plays a role in the development and support of the product and can include researchers, architects, designers, programmers, etc.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum is facilitated by a scrum master, whose role is to educate and coach teams about scrum theory and practice.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum masters have differing roles and responsibilities from team leads or project managers; project managers often have people management responsibilities, which a scrum master does not.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum teams do not involve project managers to maximize self-organisation among developers.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A sprint (also known as a *design sprint*, *iteration*, or *timebox*) is a fixed period of time wherein team members work on a specific goal.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Each sprint is normally between one week and one month, with two weeks being the most common.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The goal of the sprint should be to produce something that is tangible and "done", and the goal is treated as immutable to give the team certainty.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] If the goal needs to be changed due to a change in external priorities, the product owner or the team can terminate the sprint and start a new sprint with a new goal.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Each sprint starts with a sprint planning event in which a sprint goal is defined and priorities are chosen out of the backlog.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The suggested maximum duration of sprint planning is two hours for each week in the sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Each sprint ends with a *sprint review*, where progress is shown to stakeholders to elicit their feedback, and a *sprint retrospective* where the team identifies lessons and improvements for upcoming sprints.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Each day during a sprint, the developers hold a daily scrum (often conducted standing up) with specific guidelines, which may be facilitated by a scrum master.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Daily scrum meetings are intended to be less than 15 minutes in length, taking place at the same time and location daily.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The purpose of the meeting is to announce progress made towards the sprint goal and issues that may be hindering the goal, without going into any detailed discussion.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Once over, individual members can go into a 'breakout session' or an 'after party' for extended discussion and collaboration.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum masters are responsible for ensuring that team members use daily scrums effectively or, if team members are unable to use them, providing alternatives to achieve similar outcomes.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Conducted at the end of a sprint, a sprint review is a meeting that has a team share the work they've completed with stakeholders and liaise with them on feedback, expectations, and upcoming plans.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] At a sprint review completed deliverables are demonstrated to stakeholders.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The recommended duration for a sprint review is one hour per week of sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A sprint retrospective is a separate meeting that allows team members to internally analyze the strengths and weaknesses of the sprint, future areas of improvement, and continuous process improvement actions.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Backlog refinement is a process by which team members revise and prioritize a backlog for future sprints.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] It can be done as a separate stage done before the beginning of a new sprint or as a continuous process that team members work on by themselves.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Backlog refinement can include the breaking down of large tasks into smaller and clearer ones, the clarification of success criteria, and the revision of changing priorities and returns.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] This process was formerly known as "grooming".
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Artifacts are a means by which scrum teams manage product development by documenting work done towards the project.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] There are many kinds of scrum artifacts, with three of them being the most common: product backlog, sprint backlog, and increment.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The product backlog is a breakdown of work to be done and contains an ordered list of product requirements (such as features, bug fixes and non-functional requirements) that the team maintains for a product.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The order of a product backlog corresponds to the urgency of the task.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Common formats for backlog items include user stories and use cases.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The product backlog may also contain the product owner's assessment of business value and the team's assessment of the product's effort or complexity, which can be stated in story points using the rounded Fibonacci scale.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] These estimates try to help the product owner gauge the timeline and may influence the ordering of product backlog items.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] High-priority items at the top of the backlog are broken down into more detail for developers to work on, while tasks further down the backlog may be more vague.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The sprint backlog is the subset of items from the product backlog intended for developers to address in a particular sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Developers fill this backlog with tasks they deem appropriate to fill the sprint, using past performance to assess their capacity for each sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The scrum approach has tasks on the sprint backlog not assigned to developers by any particular individual or leader.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Developers self organize by pulling work as needed according to the backlog priority and their own capabilities and capacity, alongside other factors like learning opportunity.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] An increment is a potentially releasable output of a sprint, which meets the sprint goal and the definition of done.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] It is formed from all the completed sprint backlog items, integrated with the work of all previous sprints.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Often used in scrum, a burndown chart is a publicly displayed chart showing remaining work.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] It provides quick visualizations for reference.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The horizontal axis of the burndown chart shows the days remaining, while the vertical axis shows the amount of work remaining each day.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] During sprint planning, the ideal burndown chart is plotted.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Updated at the end of each sprint, the release burn-up chart shows progress towards delivering a forecast scope.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The horizontal axis of the release burnup chart shows the sprints in a release, while the vertical axis shows the amount of work completed at the end of each sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A team's total capability effort for a single sprint can be estimated by evaluating work completed in the last sprint.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The collection of historical "velocity" data is a guideline for assisting the team in understanding their capacity.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A team's "definition of done" is a checklist of what needs to be completed for work to be considered "done".
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] The definition of done does not necessarily guarantee that the work is ready to be released, as doing so early on in development may not be feasible, instead it represents how close the team can reasonably get with their existing capabilities.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] As the team improves, the definition of done should evolve to align with what is needed for work to be released.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A related term is the "definition of ready", which is a checklist of what needs to be completed before starting work on an item.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Some have argued that scrum events, such as daily scrums and scrum reviews, hurt productivity and waste time that could be better spent on actual productive tasks.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum has also been observed to pose difficulties for part-time or geographically distant teams; those that have highly specialized members who would be better off working by themselves or in working cliques; and those that are unsuitable for incremental and development testing.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A systematic review found "that Distributed Scrum has no impact, positive or negative on overall project success" in distributed software development.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] In September 2016, Ron Jeffries, a signatory to the Agile Manifesto, described what he called "Dark Scrum", saying that "abuses are almost inevitable until people really learn Scrum's principles and values".
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] He was particularly focused on the slow uptake of self-organisation.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum is frequently tailored or adapted in different contexts to achieve varying aims.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] A common approach to adapting scrum is the combination of scrum with other software development methodologies, as scrum does not cover the whole product development lifecycle.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Various scrum practitioners have also suggested more detailed techniques for how to apply or adapt scrum to particular problems or organizations.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Many refer to these techniques as 'patterns', an analogous use to design patterns in architecture and software.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrumban is a software production model based on scrum and kanban.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] To illustrate each stage of work, teams working in the same space often use post-it notes or a large whiteboard.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Kanban models allow a team to visualize work stages and limitations.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum of scrums is a technique to operate scrum at scale for multiple teams coordinating on the same product.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Scrum-of-scrums daily scrum meetings involve ambassadors selected from each individual team, who may be either a developer or scrum master.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] As a tool for coordination, scrum of scrums allows teams to collectively work on team-wide risks, impediments, dependencies, and assumptions (RIDAs), which may be tracked in a backlog of their own.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] Large-scale scrum is an organizational system for product development that scales scrum with varied rules and guidelines, developed by Bas Vodde and Craig Larman.
[src:agile-devops/scrum-software-development] There are two levels to the framework: the first level, designed for up to eight teams; and the second level, known as 'LeSS Huge', which can accommodate development involving hundreds of developers.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] A **software development process** prescribes a process for developing software.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] It typically divides an overall effort into smaller steps or sub-processes that are intended to ensure high-quality results.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The process may describe specific deliverables – artifacts to be created and completed.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Although not strictly limited to it, software development process often refers to the high-level process that governs the development of a software system from its beginning to its end of life – known as a methodology, model or framework.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The system development life cycle (SDLC) describes the typical phases that a development effort goes through from the beginning to the end of life for a system – including a software system.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] A methodology prescribes how engineers go about their work in order to move the system through its life cycle.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] A methodology is a classification of processes or a blueprint for a process that is devised for the SDLC.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] For example, many processes can be classified as a spiral model.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Software process and software quality are closely interrelated; some unexpected facets and effects have been observed in practice.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The SDLC drives the definition of a methodology in that a methodology must address the phases of the SDLC.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Generally, a methodology is designed to result in a high-quality system that meets or exceeds expectations (requirements) and is delivered on time and within budget even though computer systems can be complex and integrate disparate components.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Various methodologies have been devised, including waterfall, spiral, agile, rapid prototyping, incremental, and synchronize and stabilize.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] A major difference between methodologies is the degree to which the phases are sequential vs. iterative.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Agile methodologies, such as XP and scrum, focus on lightweight processes that allow for rapid changes.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Iterative methodologies, such as Rational Unified Process and dynamic systems development method, focus on stabilizing project scope and iteratively expanding or improving products.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Sequential or big-design-up-front (BDUF) models, such as waterfall, focus on complete and correct planning to guide larger projects and limit risks to successful and predictable results.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Anamorphic development is guided by project scope and adaptive iterations.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] In scrum, for example, one could say a single user story goes through all the phases of the SDLC within a two-week sprint.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] By contrast the waterfall methodology, where every business requirement is translated into feature/functional descriptions which are then all implemented typically over a period of months or longer.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] A project can include both a project life cycle (PLC) and an SDLC, which describe different activities.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] According to Taylor (2004), "the project life cycle encompasses all the activities of the project, while the systems development life cycle focuses on realizing the product requirements".
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The term *SDLC* is often used as an abbreviated version of *SDLC methodology*.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Further, some use *SDLC* and *traditional SDLC* to mean the waterfall methodology.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] According to Elliott (2004), SDLC "originated in the 1960s, to develop large scale functional business systems in an age of large scale business conglomerates.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Information systems activities revolved around heavy data processing and number crunching routines".
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The structured systems analysis and design method (SSADM) was produced for the UK government Office of Government Commerce in the 1980s.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Ever since, according to Elliott (2004), "the traditional life cycle approaches to systems development have been increasingly replaced with alternative approaches and frameworks, which attempted to overcome some of the inherent deficiencies of the traditional SDLC".
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Since DSDM in 1994, all of the methodologies on the above list except RUP have been agile methodologies - yet many organizations, especially governments, still use pre-agile processes (often waterfall or similar).
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The following are notable methodologies somewhat ordered by popularity.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Agile software development refers to a group of frameworks based on iterative development, where requirements and solutions evolve via collaboration between self-organizing cross-functional teams.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The term was coined in the year 2001 when the Agile Manifesto was formulated.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The waterfall model is a sequential development approach, in which development flows one way (like a waterfall) through the SDLC phases.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] In 1988, Barry Boehm published a software system development spiral model, which combines key aspects of the waterfall model and rapid prototyping, in an effort to combine advantages of top-down and bottom-up concepts.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] It emphases a key area many felt had been neglected by other methodologies: deliberate iterative risk analysis, particularly suited to large-scale complex systems.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Various methods combine linear and iterative methodologies, with the primary objective of reducing inherent project risk by breaking a project into smaller segments and providing more ease-of-change during the development process.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Software prototyping is about creating prototypes, i.e. incomplete versions of the software program being developed.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Rapid application development (RAD) is a methodology which favors iterative development and the rapid construction of prototypes instead of large amounts of up-front planning.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The "planning" of software developed using RAD is interleaved with writing the software itself.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The lack of extensive pre-planning generally allows software to be written much faster and makes it easier to change requirements.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Shape Up is a software development approach introduced by Basecamp in 2018.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] It is a set of principles and techniques that Basecamp developed internally to overcome the problem of projects dragging on with no clear end.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Its primary target audience is remote teams.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Shape Up has no estimation and velocity tracking, backlogs, or sprints, unlike waterfall, agile, or scrum.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Instead, those concepts are replaced with appetite, betting, and cycles.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] As of 2022, besides Basecamp, notable organizations that have adopted Shape Up include UserVoice and Block.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Chaos model has one main rule: always resolve the most important issue first.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Incremental funding methodology - an iterative approach.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Lightweight methodology - a general term for methods that only have a few rules and practices.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Structured systems analysis and design method - a specific version of waterfall.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] As part of the larger slow movement, emphasizes careful and gradual work without (or minimal) time pressures.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Slow programming aims to avoid bugs and overly quick release schedules.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] V-Model (software development) - an extension of the waterfall model.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Unified Process (UP) is an iterative software development methodology framework, based on Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] UP organizes the development of software into four phases, each consisting of one or more executable iterations of the software at that stage of development: inception, elaboration, construction, and guidelines.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The waterfall model describes the SDLC phases such that each builds on the result of the previous one.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Not every project requires that the phases be sequential.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] For relatively simple projects, phases may be combined or overlapping.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Alternative methodologies to waterfall are described and compared below.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Some process models are abstract descriptions for evaluating, comparing, and improving the specific process adopted by an organization.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 12207 is the international standard describing the method to select, implement, and monitor the life cycle for software.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] The Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI) is one of the leading models and is based on best practices.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Independent assessments grade organizations on how well they follow their defined processes, not on the quality of those processes or the software produced.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] ISO 9000 describes standards for a formally organized process to manufacture a product and the methods of managing and monitoring progress.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Although the standard was originally created for the manufacturing sector, ISO 9000 standards have been applied to software development as well.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Like CMMI, certification with ISO 9000 does not guarantee the quality of the end result, only that formalized business processes have been followed.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 15504 *Information technology—Process assessment*, a.k.a.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Software Process Improvement Capability Determination (SPICE), is a framework for the assessment of software processes.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] This standard is aimed at setting out a clear model for process comparison.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] It models processes to manage, control, guide, and monitor software development.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] This model is then used to measure what a development organization or project team actually does during software development.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] This information is analyzed to identify weaknesses and drive improvement.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] It also identifies strengths that can be continued or integrated into common practice for that organization or team.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 24744 *Software Engineering—Metamodel for Development Methodologies*, is a power type-based metamodel for software development methodologies.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Soft systems methodology is a general method for improving management processes.
[src:agile-devops/software-development-process] Method engineering is a general method for improving information system processes.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The **waterfall model** is the process of performing the typical software development life cycle (SDLC) phases in sequential order.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Each phase is completed before the next is started, and the result of each phase drives subsequent phases.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Compared to alternative SDLC methodologies such as Agile, it is among the least iterative and flexible, as progress flows largely in one direction (like a waterfall) through the phases of conception, requirements analysis, design, construction, testing, deployment, and maintenance.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The waterfall model is the earliest SDLC methodology.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] When first adopted, there were no recognized alternatives for knowledge-based creative work.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The first known presentation describing the use of such phases in software engineering was held by Herbert D.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Benington at the Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers on 29 June 1956.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] This presentation was about the development of software for SAGE.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] In 1983, Benington republished his paper with a foreword explaining that the phases were on purpose organized according to the specialization of tasks, and pointing out that the process was not in fact performed in a strict top-down fashion, but depended on a prototype.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Although the term "waterfall" is not used in the paper, the first formal, detailed diagram of the process is often cited as coming from a 1970 article by Winston W.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] However, he commented that it had major flaws stemming from how testing only happened at the end of the process, which he described as being "risky and [inviting] failure".
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The rest of his paper introduced five steps which he felt were necessary to "eliminate most of the development risks" associated with the unaltered waterfall approach.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Royce's five additional steps (which included writing complete documentation at various stages of development) never took mainstream hold, but his diagram of what he considered a flawed process became the starting point when describing a "waterfall" approach.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The earliest use of the term "waterfall" may have been in a 1976 paper by Bell and Thayer.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] In 1985, the United States Department of Defense adopted the waterfall model in the DOD-STD-2167 standard for working with software development contractors.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The model describes a linear sequence of steps.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Although various different versions can be found, the following describes the essence.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Conduct a preliminary analysis, consider alternative solutions, estimate costs and benefits, and submit a preliminary plan with recommendations.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Decompose project goals into defined functions and operations.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] This involves gathering and interpreting facts, diagnosing problems, and recommending changes.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] At this step, desired features and operations are detailed, including screen layouts, business rules, process diagrams, pseudocode, and other deliverables.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Assemble the modules in a testing environment.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Check for errors, bugs, and interoperability.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] This may involve training users, deploying hardware, and loading information from the prior system.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Monitor the system to assess its ongoing fitness.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Make modest changes and fixes as needed.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] This helps maintain the quality of the system.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Continual monitoring and updates ensure the system remains effective and high-quality.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The system and the process are reviewed.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Relevant questions include whether the newly implemented system meets requirements and achieves project goals, whether the system is usable, reliable/available, properly scaled and fault-tolerant.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Process checks include review of timelines and expenses, as well as user acceptance.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] At end of life, plans are developed for discontinuing the system and transitioning to its replacement.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Related information and infrastructure must be repurposed, archived, discarded, or destroyed, while appropriately protecting security.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Time spent early in the software production cycle can reduce costs at later stages.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] For example, a problem found in the early stages (such as requirements specification) is cheaper to fix than the same bug found later on in the process (by a factor of 50 to 200).
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] In common practice, waterfall methodologies result in a project schedule with 20–40% of the time invested for the first two phases, 30–40% of the time to coding, and the rest dedicated to testing and implementation.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] With the project organization needing to be highly structured, most medium and large projects will include a detailed set of procedures and controls, which regulate every process on the project.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] A further argument supporting the waterfall model is that it places emphasis on documentation (such as requirements documents and design documents) as well as source code.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] In less thoroughly designed and documented methodologies, knowledge is lost if team members leave before the project is completed, and it may be difficult for a project to recover from the loss.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] If a fully working design document is present (as is the intent of big design up front and the waterfall model), new team members and new teams should be able to familiarise themselves to the project by reading the documents.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] The waterfall model provides a structured approach; the model itself progresses linearly through discrete, easily understandable and explainable phases and thus is easy to understand.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] It also provides easily identifiable milestones in the development process, often being used as a beginning example of a development model in many software engineering texts and courses.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Clients may not know the exact requirements before they see working software and thus change their requirements further on, leading to redesign, redevelopment, and retesting, and increased costs.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Designers may not be aware of future difficulties when designing a new software product or feature, in which case revising the design initially can increase efficiency in comparison to a design not built to account for newly discovered constraints, requirements, or problems.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Organisations may attempt to deal with a lack of concrete requirements from clients by employing systems analysts to examine existing manual systems and analyse what they do and how they might be replaced.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] However, in practice, it is difficult to sustain a strict separation between systems analysis and programming, as implementing any non-trivial system will often expose issues and edge cases that the systems analyst did not consider.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Some organisations, such as the United States Department of Defense, now have a stated preference against waterfall-type methodologies, starting with MIL-STD-498 released in 1994, which encourages *evolutionary acquisition* and *iterative and incremental development*.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] In response to perceived problems with the original, pure waterfall model, many modified versions have been devised to address the problems.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] These include the rapid development models that Steve McConnell calls "modified waterfalls": Peter DeGrace's "sashimi model" (waterfall with overlapping phases), waterfall with subprojects, and waterfall with risk reduction.
[src:agile-devops/waterfall-model] Other software development model combinations such as "incremental waterfall model" also exist.
